==English==

===Etymology===
Literal translation of Ancient Greek εξεμνκτηριζον from εξ (intensifier with additional senses of ''out from'' or ''of the nature of'') and μνκτηριζον (to mock by turning up one's nose, from the base μνκτηρ (snout, nose))

===Verb===
'''[[turn]] [[up]] one's [[nose]] (at something)'''
# {{idiom}} To [[sneer]]
#*'''1958:''' annotated translation based on documents deriving from postulated '''c.85''' Greek text attrib to Luke (εξεμνκτηριζον δε και οι αρχοντες συν αυτοις λεγοντες αλλους εσωσεν σωσατω εαυτον ει ουτος εστιν ο χριστος ο του θεου εκλεκτος): Lockman Foundation, ''The Amplified New Testament'' used in '''1965''' Zondervan Corporation, ''The Amplified Bible, Luke 23:35'' - but the rulers scoffed and sneered (literal translation: '''turned up their noses''') at Him, saying, He rescued others; let Him now rescue Himself, if He is the Christ (the Messiah) of God, His Chosen One!
# {{idiom}} To [[refuse]], especially as due to [[pride]] or [[status]]
#:''I tried to help, but they '''turned up their noses''' at my advice.''

